{"title_page": "Raumesh Akbari", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name=Raumesh Akbari \n|image=\n|caption=\n|state_senate   = Tennessee\n|state         = Tennessee\n|district      = 29th\n|term_start    = January 8, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|preceded      = [[Lee Harris (politician)|Lee Harris]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1984|4|14}}<ref>https://sos-tn-gov-files.s3.amazonaws.com/Pages%2055%20-%20164%20from%202017-2018BlueBook.pdf</ref>\n|state_house1 = Tennessee\n|state1       = Tennessee\n|district1    = 91st\n|term1        = November 2013 \u2013 January 8, 2019 \n|predecessor1   = [[Lois DeBerry]]\n|successor1    = London Lamar \n| office2 = Chair of the Tennessee Black Caucus of State Legislators\n| term2 = February 2017-Present\n| predecessor2 = [[Brenda Gilmore]]\n| successor2 =\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| otherparty    = \n| relations     = \n| spouse        =\n| children      = \n| residence     = [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| occupation    = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = [http://www.raumeshakbari.com/ Official website]\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Raumesh Aleza Akbari''' (''ruh-MESH'' ''ack-BERRY'') is an American politician and member of the [[Tennessee Senate]] for the 29th district since 2019. She formerly was a member of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]] for the 91st district. She currently serves as a member of the Criminal Justice Committee, Education-Administration and Planning Committee, and the Criminal Justice Subcommittee.<ref name=\"tn.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitol.tn.gov/house/members/h91.html|title=Representatives \u2013 TN General Assembly|website=www.capitol.tn.gov}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nAkbari, who has a twin sister named Raumina, is the daughter of two trichologists.<ref name=\"stockard\">{{cite news|last1=Stockard|first1=Sam|title=Akbari Proving to be Worthy Successor to Iconic DeBerry|url=https://www.memphisdailynews.com/news/2016/may/6/akbari-proving-to-be-worthy-successor-to-iconic-deberry/|accessdate=27 July 2016|publisher=Memphis Daily News|date=6 May 2016}}</ref> Akbari is a 2002 graduate of [[Cordova High School (Tennessee)|Cordova High School]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. She attended [[Washington University]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], where she graduated in 2006 with a BA in [[African American studies]] and a minor in [[political science]]. In 2009 Akbari received her [[Juris Doctorate]] from [[St. Louis University School of Law]]. She currently handles legal affairs and human resources for Akbari Corp\u2014a small business founded by her parents in 1981.<ref name=\"akbari91.com\">http://www.akbari91.com/about-representative-akbari.html</ref>\n\nAkbari is a member of the [[American Bar Association]], Ben F. Jones Chapter of the National Bar Association, Memphis Bar Association, [[Phi Alpha Delta]] Legal Fraternity, [[NAACP]], Memphis Urban League Young Professionals and the Democratic Party of Shelby County.  She also actively volunteers with [[Meals on Wheels]] through the Metropolitan Inter-Faith Association and is a member of the Memphis \"Voter Registration and Community Organization, Inc.<ref name=\"tn.gov\"/>\"\n\nAkbari worships at New Hope Baptist Church.<ref name=\"akbari91.com\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Akbari was elected by her peers to serve Tennessee as the state co-director of Women in Government, a national non-profit, non-partisan organization of female state legislators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pridepublishinggroup.com/pride/2015/01/20/gilmore-akbari-elected-to-leadership-role-with-women-in-government/|title=Gilmore & Akbari elected to leadership role with Women In Government \u2013 Nashville PRIDE, Inc.|website=pridepublishinggroup.com}}</ref> In 2017 selected by the Tennessee Black Caucus of State Legislators to serve as that organization's<ref>http://tsdmemphis.com/news/2017/feb/08/tennessee-black-caucus-state-legislators-elect-lea/</ref> Chair. Akbari currently serves as the Treasurer of the National Black Caucus of State Legislators, the Financial Secretary of the National Organization of Black Elected Legislative Women, and as a co-chair of the Interbranch Affairs Committee for the Council of State Government.\n\n==Public service==\n\nIn early 2014, [[Shelby County Schools (Tennessee)|Shelby County Schools]] announced a plan to close 13 campuses in southwest and northwest Memphis, including Alcy Elementary.<ref>http://www.scsk12.org/uf/standard/ckeditor/samples/ckfinder/userfiles/files/2014/news/2014-15%20School%20Closures.pdf</ref> A \"Save-Alcy\" group was formed by Akbari and other parent and community volunteers with the goal of keeping Alcy Elementary open. After a month of negations, the board reversed its decision to close the Alcy campus citing the more than 60 community leaders who stepped-up and committed to volunteer at least three hours at the elementary school each week. For her efforts, Akbari was hailed as a \"champion of a school rarely in the limelight.<ref>http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/alcy-elementary-in-memphis-has-happy-ending-in-closing-story-ep-355954519-326001831.html</ref>\"\n\nAkbari has also worked to restore historic local grave sites, including those at Mount Caramel and Hollywood cemeteries which were previously inaccessible  due to overgrowth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/23369749/citizens-are-fixing-a-neglected-cemetery|title=Citizens fixing neglected cemetery|first=Kontji|last=Anthony|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Legislation==\nFollowing a 2014 incident at the Galilee Cemetery in Memphis, Akbari sponsored legislation to streamline burial practices, allowing families to know where a loved one is buried.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wreg.com/2014/01/28/state-lawmaker-considering-tougher-penalties-for-cemetery-owners/|title=State Lawmaker Considering Tougher Penalties For Cemetery Owners|date=29 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAkbari has advocated for the expansion of Tennessee's Medicaid program, as well as a state-level law that would ensure women receive equal pay for equal work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tndemocrats.com/raumesh_akbari|title=Get to know Raumesh Akbari|website=www.tndemocrats.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065650/http://www.tndemocrats.com/raumesh_akbari|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n\n* \"[[Paul Robeson]] Leadership Award\" from [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]]<ref name=\"tn.gov\"/>\n* \"2014 20 Under 30\" list by the [[Memphis Flyer]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/2030/Content?oid=3593239|title=20|first=Richard|last=Alley|website=Memphis Flyer}}</ref>\n* \"Spark Award\" from N.O.B.E.L. ([http://nobel-women.org/ National Organization of Black Elected Legislative Women])<ref>https://www.slcatlanta.org/CALS/pubs/CALS%20Newsletter%20Winter%202015.pdf</ref>\n* \"Rising State Leaders Program\" international participant, selected by the Consul-General of the Embassy of Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/JacksonBaker/archives/2015/06/08/rep-akbari-selected-for-canadian-tour-as-a-rising-state-leader|title=Rep. Akbari Selected for Canadian Tour as a \"Rising State Leader\"|first=Jackson|last=Baker|publisher=}}</ref>\n* \"Emerging Leaders Program\" participant, selected by the [http://www.sllf.org/ State Legislative Leaders Foundation],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tnreport.com/2015/05/28/akbari-picked-attend-emerging-leaders-program/|title=Akbari Picked to Attend for 'Emerging Leaders Program' \u2013 TNReport|date=28 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Election 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tn.gov/sos/election/results/20141104_CountyTotals_01.pdf|title=Elections \u2013 Tennessee Secretary of State|website=tn.gov}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 8,053\n  |percentage = 81.93\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Samuel A. Arthur Watkins\n  |votes      = 1,777\n  |percentage = 18.07\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Primary Election 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tn.gov/sos/election/results/20140807_DemocraticPrimaryCounty.pdf|title=Elections \u2013 Tennessee Secretary of State|website=tn.gov}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 3,964\n  |percentage = 55.74\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Doris DeBerry-Bradshaw\n  |votes      = 3,147\n  |percentage = 44.26\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Special Election 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://knoxblogs.com/humphreyhill/2013/11/22/raumesh-akbari-wins-house-district-91-special-election/|title=Raumesh Akbari wins House District 91 special election|date=22 November 2013|publisher=}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 3,087\n  |percentage = 89\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = James Tomaski\n  |votes      = 369\n  |percentage = 11\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Special Primary Election 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memphisdailynews.com/news/2013/oct/9/akbari-wins-democratic-state-house-primary/|title=Akbari Wins Democratic State House Primary|publisher=}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 502\n  |percentage = 28\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Terica Lamb\n  |votes      = 399\n  |percentage = 22\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Kemba Ford\n  |votes      = 355\n  |percentage = 20\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Joshua Forbes\n  |votes      = 261\n  |percentage = 14\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Clifford Lewis\n  |votes      = 134\n  |percentage = 08\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Doris DeBerry-Bradshaw\n  |votes      = 111\n  |percentage = 06\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Kermit Moore\n  |votes      = 47\n  |percentage = 02\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==http://www.raumeshakbari.com/home.html ==\n* [http://www.akbari91.com/ Website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-tn-hs}}\n{{succession box\n| before= [[Lois DeBerry]]\n| title = Tennessee State Representative, 91st District\n| years = 2013-2019\n| after = London Lamar\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Tennessee State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akbari, Raumesh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis alumni]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name=Raumesh Akbari \n|image=\n|caption=\n|state_senate   = Tennessee\n|state         = Tennessee\n|district      = 29th\n|term_start    = January 8, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|preceded      = [[Lee Harris (politician)|Lee Harris]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1984|4|14}}<ref>https://sos-tn-gov-files.s3.amazonaws.com/Pages%2055%20-%20164%20from%202017-2018BlueBook.pdf</ref>\n|state_house1 = Tennessee\n|state1       = Tennessee\n|district1    = 91st\n|term1        = November 2013 \u2013 January 8, 2019 \n|predecessor1   = [[Lois DeBerry]]\n|successor1    = London Lamar \n| office2 = Chair of the Tennessee Black Caucus of State Legislators\n| term2 = February 2017-Present\n| predecessor2 = [[Brenda Gilmore]]\n| successor2 =\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| otherparty    = \n| relations     = \n| spouse        =\n| children      = \n| residence     = [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| occupation    = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = [http://www.raumeshakbari.com/ Official website]\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Raumesh Aleza Akbari''' (''ruh-MESH'' ''ack-BERRY'') is an American politician and member of the [[Tennessee Senate]] for the 29th district since 2019. She formerly was a member of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]] for the 91st district. She currently serves as a member of the Criminal Justice Committee, Education-Administration and Planning Committee, and the Criminal Justice Subcommittee.<ref name=\"tn.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitol.tn.gov/house/members/h91.html|title=Representatives - TN General Assembly|website=www.capitol.tn.gov}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nAkbari, who has a twin sister named Raumina, is the daughter of two trichologists.<ref name=\"stockard\">{{cite news|last1=Stockard|first1=Sam|title=Akbari Proving to be Worthy Successor to Iconic DeBerry|url=https://www.memphisdailynews.com/news/2016/may/6/akbari-proving-to-be-worthy-successor-to-iconic-deberry/|accessdate=27 July 2016|publisher=Memphis Daily News|date=6 May 2016}}</ref> Akbari is a 2002 graduate of [[Cordova High School (Tennessee)|Cordova High School]] in [[Memphis, TN]]. She attended [[Washington University]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] where she graduated in 2006 with a BA in [[African American studies]] and a minor in [[political science]]. In 2009 Akbari received her [[Juris Doctorate]] from [[St. Louis University School of Law]]. She currently handles legal affairs and human resources for Akbari Corp\u2014a small business founded by her parents in 1981.<ref name=\"akbari91.com\">http://www.akbari91.com/about-representative-akbari.html</ref>\n\nAkbari is a member of the [[American Bar Association]], Ben F. Jones Chapter of the National Bar Association, Memphis Bar Association, [[Phi Alpha Delta]] Legal Fraternity, [[NAACP]], Memphis Urban League Young Professionals and the Democratic Party of Shelby County.  She also actively volunteers with [[Meals on Wheels]] through the Metropolitan Inter-Faith Association and is a member of the Memphis \"Voter Registration and Community Organization, Inc.<ref name=\"tn.gov\"/>\"\n\nAkbari worships at New Hope Baptist Church.<ref name=\"akbari91.com\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Akbari was elected by her peers to serve Tennessee as the state co-director of Women in Government, a national non-profit, non-partisan organization of female state legislators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pridepublishinggroup.com/pride/2015/01/20/gilmore-akbari-elected-to-leadership-role-with-women-in-government/|title=Gilmore & Akbari elected to leadership role with Women In Government - Nashville PRIDE, Inc.|website=pridepublishinggroup.com}}</ref> In 2017 selected by the Tennessee Black Caucus of State Legislators to serve as that organization's<ref>http://tsdmemphis.com/news/2017/feb/08/tennessee-black-caucus-state-legislators-elect-lea/</ref> Chair. Akbari currently serves as the Treasurer of the National Black Caucus of State Legislators, the Financial Secretary of the National Organization of Black Elected Legislative Women, and as a co-chair of the Interbranch Affairs Committee for the Council of State Government.\n\n==Public Service==\n\nIn early 2014, [[Shelby County Schools (Tennessee)|Shelby County Schools]] announced a plan to close 13 campuses in southwest and northwest Memphis, including Alcy Elementary.<ref>http://www.scsk12.org/uf/standard/ckeditor/samples/ckfinder/userfiles/files/2014/news/2014-15%20School%20Closures.pdf</ref> A \"Save-Alcy\" group was formed by Akbari and other parent and community volunteers with the goal of keeping Alcy Elementary open. After a month of negations, the board reversed its decision to close the Alcy campus citing the more than 60 community leaders who stepped-up and committed to volunteer at least three hours at the elementary school each week. For her efforts, Akbari was hailed as a \"champion of a school rarely in the limelight.<ref>http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/alcy-elementary-in-memphis-has-happy-ending-in-closing-story-ep-355954519-326001831.html</ref>\"\n\nAkbari has also worked to restore historic local grave sites, including those at Mount Caramel and Hollywood cemeteries which were previously inaccessible  due to overgrowth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmcactionnews5.com/story/23369749/citizens-are-fixing-a-neglected-cemetery|title=Citizens fixing neglected cemetery|first=Kontji|last=Anthony|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Legislation==\nFollowing a 2014 incident at the Galilee Cemetery in Memphis, Akbari sponsored legislation to streamline burial practices, allowing families to know where a loved one is buried.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wreg.com/2014/01/28/state-lawmaker-considering-tougher-penalties-for-cemetery-owners/|title=State Lawmaker Considering Tougher Penalties For Cemetery Owners|date=29 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAkbari has advocated for the expansion of Tennessee's Medicaid program, as well as a state-level law that would ensure women receive equal pay for equal work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tndemocrats.com/raumesh_akbari|title=Get to know Raumesh Akbari|website=www.tndemocrats.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065650/http://www.tndemocrats.com/raumesh_akbari|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honors & Awards==\n\n* \"[[Paul Robeson]] Leadership Award\" from [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]]<ref name=\"tn.gov\"/>\n* \"2014 20 Under 30\" list by the [[Memphis Flyer]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/2030/Content?oid=3593239|title=20|first=Richard|last=Alley|website=Memphis Flyer}}</ref>\n* \"Spark Award\" from N.O.B.E.L. ([http://nobel-women.org/ National Organization of Black Elected Legislative Women])<ref>https://www.slcatlanta.org/CALS/pubs/CALS%20Newsletter%20Winter%202015.pdf</ref>\n* \"Rising State Leaders Program\" international participant, selected by the Consul-General of the Embassy of Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/JacksonBaker/archives/2015/06/08/rep-akbari-selected-for-canadian-tour-as-a-rising-state-leader|title=Rep. Akbari Selected for Canadian Tour as a \"Rising State Leader\"|first=Jackson|last=Baker|publisher=}}</ref>\n* \"Emerging Leaders Program\" participant, selected by the [http://www.sllf.org/ State Legislative Leaders Foundation],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tnreport.com/2015/05/28/akbari-picked-attend-emerging-leaders-program/|title=Akbari Picked to Attend for 'Emerging Leaders Program' - TNReport|date=28 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral History==\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Election 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tn.gov/sos/election/results/20141104_CountyTotals_01.pdf|title=Elections - Tennessee Secretary of State|website=tn.gov}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 8,053\n  |percentage = 81.93\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Samuel A. Arthur Watkins\n  |votes      = 1,777\n  |percentage = 18.07\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Primary Election 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tn.gov/sos/election/results/20140807_DemocraticPrimaryCounty.pdf|title=Elections - Tennessee Secretary of State|website=tn.gov}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 3,964\n  |percentage = 55.74\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Doris DeBerry-Bradshaw\n  |votes      = 3,147\n  |percentage = 44.26\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Tennessee House of Representatives Special Election 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://knoxblogs.com/humphreyhill/2013/11/22/raumesh-akbari-wins-house-district-91-special-election/|title=Raumesh Akbari wins House District 91 special election|date=22 November 2013|publisher=}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Raumesh Akbari\n  |votes      = 3,087\n  |percentage = 89\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = James Tomaski\n  |votes      = 369\n  |percentage = 11\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election 