}}\n\nThese figures are not fully representative of developments over the weekend of 4 and 5 April because of the move to a new process for reporting deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus in Scotland|last=|first=|date=|website=Scottish Government|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406135647/https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ScotlandCumulativeCasesByRegion13April2020.svg|alt=|frameless|1170x1170px]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Scotland|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Scotland]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Rbstrachan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link to Heriot-Watt University wiki page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Scotland"}
{"title_page": "I Still Call Australia Home", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Still Call Australia Home\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     = [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]]\n| album      = [[Bi-Coastal]]\n| EP         =\n| language   = English\n| written    =\n| published  =\n| released   = June 1980\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1979\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     = Peter Allen\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   = Peter Allen\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''I Still Call Australia Home'''\" is a song written and performed by [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]] in 1980. In it, Allen sings of Australian expatriates' longing for home.\n\n==Significance to Australian culture==\nIt has been used to signify [[Australian patriotism]] and [[nostalgia]] for home. An example is the series of [[Qantas]] television commercials where it was sung either by individual Australian musicians or one of several Australian youth choirs.<ref name=\"InspirationRoom\">{{cite web |url=http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/2006/qantas-i-still-call-australia-home |title=Qantas I Still Call Australia Home |publisher=The Inspiration Room Daily |accessdate=2 July 2009 |author=Duncan Macleod}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1984 Summer Olympics]]' ''Opening Gala'' TV special (in [[Los Angeles]]), [[Olivia Newton-John]] performed this song from [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] with the choir in a medley with \"[[Waltzing Matilda]]\". Later, both songs were used in the musical about Allen's life, ''[[The Boy from Oz]]'', in which [[Hugh Jackman]] starred as Allen.\n\n\"I Still Call Australia Home\" was added to the [[National Film and Sound Archive]]'s [[Sounds of Australia]] registry in 2013.<ref>National Film and Sound Archive: [http://nfsa.gov.au/collection/sound/sounds-australia/complete-list/ Sounds of Australia].</ref>\n\nIn [[Australian English]] speech of earlier generations, \"home\" referred to the mother-country - Britain.<ref>\n{{oed | home}} - \"Formerly used with reference to Britain by inhabitants of (former) British dependencies [...].\" \n</ref>\nThus by contrast, \"calling Australia home\" became for a period a particularly piquant expression of [[Australian nationalism|Australian identity]].\n\n==Charts==\n\"I Still Call Australia Home\" peaked at number 72 on the [[Kent Music Report|Australian singles chart]] in June 1980<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/imfQf27.png|title=Kent Music Report No 312 \u2013 Week Ending 16 June 1980|publisher=Imgur.com (original document published by [[Kent Music Report]])|accessdate=12 August 2017}} N.B. The HP column displays the highest peak reached.</ref> when it was originally released,<ref>{{cite book|first=David|last=Kent|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|edition=Illustrated|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives|year=1993|page=15|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref> but re-entered [[ARIA Charts|the charts]] and peaked at number 60 in September 2015 following the screening of the mini-series ''[[Peter Allen: Not the Boy Next Door]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-singles-justin-bieber-what-do-you-mean-keeps-top-spot-20150919|title=ARIA Singles: Justin Bieber 'What Do You Mean' Keeps Top Spot|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|publisher=Noise11|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Use==\n* The song was used in the evening closing sequence for [[Tasmania]]n television station [[TNT (TV station)|TNT-9 Launceston]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Xvo0L_oUWQ |title=TNT 9 Closedown Early 1980s |accessdate=1 September 2010 |date=c. 1980}}</ref> and later by [[TasTV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNWNSGDDhXY |title=TAS TV End of Transmission |accessdate=16 March 2012 |date=c. 1986}}</ref>\n* In one version of the song popularly used by Qantas, \"Rio\" is replaced by \"[[Rome]]\" as Qantas does not operate flights to [[Rio de Janeiro]], but flew to the Italian capital at the time the video was made.<ref name=\"InspirationRoom\"/>\n** The version of the song used by Qantas in its 2009 advertisement replaces the entire first verse with one sung in ''[[Kala Lagaw Ya]]'', a dialect of the [[Torres Strait Islands]].<ref name=\"InspirationRoom\"/> This version was performed by the [[Gondwana Choirs|Gondwana National Indigenous Children's Choir]] and the [[Gondwana Choirs|Sydney Children's Choir]] as well as the Australian Girls Choir and National Boys Choir.\n** Qantas later reused the song as part of safety videos since 2018, with the 2018 safety video recorded in many parts around the world, including New York and London. In addition, \"Rio\" was used in this version of the song instead of \"Rome\".<ref>[https://www.qantasnewsroom.com.au/media-releases/aussies-being-aussies-around-the-world-in-new-safety-video/]</ref> When Qantas was celebrating the centennial anniversary of its foundation, the instrumental version of the song tailored to each time period portrayed in the safety video (with a children's choir singing at the end).<ref>https://www.qantasnewsroom.com.au/media-releases/one-hundred-years-of-style-and-innovation-in-new-qantas-safety-video/</ref>\n* The song is a popular inclusion in the repertoire of several [[Music of Wales|Welsh]] [[male voice choir]]s, including the [[Australian Welsh Male Choir]] and [[Morriston Orpheus Choir]]. The Welsh version replaces \"[[London]]\" in the line \"from [[New York City|New York]], to [[Rome]], and old London town\", with \"[[Swansea]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005LNVV |title=Wonderful Welsh Choirs}} (track 11)</ref>\n* Australian comedy team [[The Chaser]] composed a parody of the Qantas version of the song, called \"I Still Call Australia 51 per cent Home\" in response to Qantas outsourcing some of its engineering services to [[Singapore Airlines]] and [[Lufthansa]].<ref name=\"TschmuckPearce2013\">{{cite book|author1=Peter Tschmuck|author2=Philip L. Pearce|author3=Steven Campbell|title=Music Business and the Experience Economy: The Australasian Case|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UUM_AAAAQBAJ|date=16 April 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-27898-3|page=164}}</ref>\n* The song was performed by [[Chris Lilley (comedian)|Chris Lilley]] in episodes one and two of \"[[We Can Be Heroes: Finding The Australian of the Year]]\" (2005).{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n* The song was performed by singer [[Kylie Minogue]] in the [[Sound Relief]] concert in benefit of the victims of the [[Black Saturday bushfires|Australian Bushfires]] on 14 March 2009.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n* The song featured as pre-game entertainment at the [[2009 AFL Grand Final]], performed by the 'Qantas choir' and the Gondwana National Indigenous Children's Choir.<ref>{{cite book\n| author = Gondwana Choirs Ltd\n| url = http://www.gondwanachoirs.com.au/pdfs/GC%20Final%202009%20Signed%20Report.pdf\n| title = Annual Report 2009\n| series = Annual report\n| publication-date = 2010\n| page = 7\n| location = [[Sydney]]\n}}</ref>\n* The song was performed by [[Nicole Kidman]], [[Keith Urban]], [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Olivia Newton-John]] and [[Russell Crowe]] to close [[Oprah Winfrey]]'s Australian Adventure during her final season on broadcast television. This performance originally aired on US television on Friday, 21 January 2011.\n* The naming ceremony for Qantas' A380, VH-OQA, the [[Nancy Bird Walton]], the flagship of their fleet, features a choir singing this song\n*The song was adapted and translated into French by Sylvie Boisel.  The title is L'Australie est ma patrie.   She performed it at [[Sydney Town Hall]] for the [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[John Howard]] and the [[Wallabies (rugby union)|Wallabies]] in 2007.\n*The song was performed by a choir at the opening ceremonies of the [[1982 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Brisbane]].\n*Australian comedian and musician [[Tim Minchin]] uploaded a parody of the song called \"I Still Call Australia Homophobic\" to his Facebook page<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/timminchin/videos/10155430722376826/ |accessdate=11 August 2017 |title=Tim Minchin - A heartfelt song to my homeland...}}</ref> in reference to the [[same-sex marriage]] debate and [[Australian survey, 2017 (Marriage)|proposed 2017 survey]] in Australia.<ref name=Aus17>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/tim-minchin-i-still-call-australia-home-ophobic/news-story/75b190ea42a532af92fefaa57aacb8d8|title=Minchin: 'I still call Australia homophobic'|date=11 August 2017|author=Caroline Overington|work=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n*The Australian hip hop group TLK used the song as the inspiration for their 2006 song \"I still call Australia home\" which referenced historical violence against Aboriginals.<ref name=\"Minestrelli2016\">{{cite book|author=Chiara Minestrelli|title=Australian Indigenous Hip Hop: The Politics of Culture, Identity, and Spirituality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vCslDwAAQBAJ|date=26 October 2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-21754-1|page=216}}</ref><ref name=\"PorfilioRoychoudhury2014\">{{cite book|author1=Brad Porfilio|author2=Debangshu Roychoudhury|author3=Lauren M. Gardner|title=See You at the Crossroads: Hip Hop Scholarship at the Intersections: Dialectical Harmony, Ethics, Aesthetics, and Panoply of Voices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-qZBAAAQBAJ|date=23 September 2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-94-6209-674-5|page=136}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3z1scL4kLBs ''I Still Call Australia Home''] TVC (2004)\n* Lyrics: [http://lyriki.com/Peter_Allen:I_Still_Call_Australia_Home Peter Allen - ''I Still Call Australia Home'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m1Oji__RJc0 ''I Still Call Australia Home''] performed in French by Sylvie Boisel\n\n{{Peter Allen}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Australian patriotic songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Still Call Australia Home\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     = [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]]\n| album      = [[Bi-Coastal]]\n| EP         =\n| language   = English\n| written    =\n| published  =\n| released   = June 1980\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1979\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     = Peter Allen\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   = Peter Allen\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''I Still Call Australia Home'''\" is a song written and performed by [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]] in 1980. In it, Allen sings of Australian expatriates' longing for home.\n==Significance to Australian culture==\nIt has been used to signify [[Australian patriotism]] and [[nostalgia]] for home. An example is the series of [[Qantas]] television commercials where it was sung either by individual Australian musicians or one of several Australian youth choirs.<ref name=\"InspirationRoom\">{{cite web |url=http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/2006/qantas-i-still-call-australia-home |title=Qantas I Still Call Australia Home |publisher=The Inspiration Room Daily |accessdate=2 July 2009 |author=Duncan Macleod}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1984 Summer Olympics]]' ''Opening Gala'' TV special (in [[Los Angeles]]), [[Olivia Newton-John]] performed this song from [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] with the choir in a medley with \"[[Waltzing Matilda]]\". Later, both songs were used in the musical about Allen's life, ''[[The Boy from Oz]]'', in which [[Hugh Jackman]] starred as Allen.\n\n\"I Still Call Australia Home\" was added to the [[National Film and Sound Archive]]'s [[Sounds of Australia]] registry in 2013.<ref>National Film and Sound Archive: [http://nfsa.gov.au/collection/sound/sounds-australia/complete-list/ Sounds of Australia].</ref>\n\nIn [[Australian English]] speech of earlier generations, \"home\" referred to the mother-country - Britain.<ref>\n{{oed | home}} - \"Formerly used with reference to Britain by inhabitants of (former) British dependencies [...].\" \n</ref>\nThus by contrast, \"calling Australia home\" became for a period a particularly piquant expression of [[Australian nationalism | Australian identity]].\n\n==Charts==\n\"I Still Call Australia Home\" peaked at number 72 on the [[Kent Music Report|Australian singles chart]] in June 1980<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/imfQf27.png|title=Kent Music Report No 312 \u2013 Week Ending 16 June 1980|publisher=Imgur.com (original document published by [[Kent Music Report]])|accessdate=12 August 2017}} N.B. The HP column displays the highest peak reached.</ref> when it was originally released,<ref>{{cite book|first=David|last=Kent|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|edition=Illustrated|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives|year=1993|page=15|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref> but re-entered [[ARIA Charts|the charts]] and peaked at number 60 in September 2015 following the screening of the mini-series ''[[Peter Allen: Not the Boy Next Door]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-singles-justin-bieber-what-do-you-mean-keeps-top-spot-20150919|title=ARIA Singles: Justin Bieber 'What Do You Mean' Keeps Top Spot|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|publisher=Noise11|date=19 September 2015|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Use==\n* The song was used in the evening closing sequence for [[Tasmania]]n television station [[TNT (TV station)|TNT-9 Launceston]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Xvo0L_oUWQ |title=TNT 9 Closedown Early 1980s |accessdate=1 September 2010 |date=c. 1980}}</ref> and later by [[TasTV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DNWNSGDDhXY |title=TAS TV End of Transmission |accessdate=16 March 2012 |date=c. 1986}}</ref>\n* In one version of the song popularly used by Qantas, \"Rio\" is replaced by \"[[Rome]]\" as Qantas does not operate flights to [[Rio de Janeiro]], but flew to the Italian capital at the time the video was made.<ref name=\"InspirationRoom\"/>\n** The version of the song used by Qantas in its 2009 advertisement replaces the entire first verse with one sung in ''[[Kala Lagaw Ya]]'', a dialect of the [[Torres Strait Islands]].<ref name=\"InspirationRoom\"/> This version was performed by the [[Gondwana Choirs|Gondwana National Indigenous Children's Choir]] and the [[Gondwana Choirs|Sydney Children's Choir]] as well as the Australian Girls Choir and National Boys Choir.\n** Qantas later reused the song as part of safety videos since 2018, with the 2018 safety video recorded in many parts around the world, including New York and London. In addition, \"Rio\" was used in this version of the song instead of \"Rome\".<ref>[https://www.qantasnewsroom.com.au/media-releases/aussies-being-aussies-around-the-world-in-new-safety-video/]</ref> When Qantas was celebrating the centennial anniversary of its foundation, the instrumental version of the song tailored to each time period portrayed in the safety video (with a children's choir singing at the end).<ref>https://www.qantasnewsroom.com.au/media-releases/one-hundred-years-of-style-and-innovation-in-new-qantas-safety-video/</ref>\n* The song is a popular inclusion in the repertoire of several [[Music of Wales|Welsh]] [[male voice choir]]s, including the [[Australian Welsh Male Choir]] and [[Morriston Orpheus Choir]]. The Welsh version replaces \"[[London]]\" in the line \"from [[New York City|New York]], to [[Rome]], and old London town\", with \"[[Swansea]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005LNVV |title=Wonderful Welsh Choirs}} (track 11)</ref>\n* Australian comedy team [[The Chaser]] composed a parody of the Qantas version of the song, called \"I Still Call Australia 51 per cent Home\" in response to Qantas outsourcing some of its engineering services to [[Singapore Airlines]] and [[Lufthansa]].<ref name=\"TschmuckPearce2013\">{{cite book|author1=Peter Tschmuck|author2=Philip L. Pearce|author3=Steven Campbell|title=Music Business and the Experience Economy: The Australasian Case|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UUM_AAAAQBAJ|date=16 April 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-27898-3|page=164}}</ref>\n* The song was performed by [[Chris Lilley (comedian)|Chris Lilley]] in episodes one and two of \"[[We Can Be Heroes: Finding The Australian of the Year]]\" (2005).{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n* The song was performed by singer [[Kylie Minogue]] in the [[Sound Relief]] concert in benefit of the victims of the [[Black Saturday bushfires|Australian Bushfires]] on 14 March 2009.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n* The song featured as pre-game entertainment at the [[2009 AFL Grand Final]], performed by the 'Qantas choir' and the Gondwana National Indigenous Children's Choir.<ref>{{cite book\n| author = Gondwana Choirs Ltd\n| url = http://www.gondwanachoirs.com.au/pdfs/GC%20Final%202009%20Signed%20Report.pdf\n| title = Annual Report 2009\n| series = Annual report\n| publication-date = 2010\n| page = 7\n| location = [[Sydney]]\n}}</ref>\n* The song was performed by [[Nicole Kidman]], [[Keith Urban]], [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Olivia Newton-John]] and [[Russell Crowe]] to close [[Oprah Winfrey]]'s Australian Adventure during her final season on broadcast television. This performance originally aired on US television on Friday, 21 January 2011.\n* The naming ceremony for Qantas' A380, VH-OQA, the [[Nancy Bird Walton]], the flagship of their fleet, features a choir singing this song\n*The song was adapted and translated into French by Sylvie Boisel.  The title is L'Australie est ma patrie.   She performed it at [[Sydney Town Hall]] for the [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[John Howard]] and the [[Wallabies (rugby union)|Wallabies]] in 2007.\n*The song was performed by a choir at the opening ceremonies of the [[1982 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Brisbane]].\n*Australian comedian and musician [[Tim Minchin]] uploaded a parody of the song called \"I Still Call Australia Homophobic\" to his Facebook page<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/timminchin/videos/10155430722376826/ |accessdate=11 August 2017 |title=Tim Minchin - A heartfelt song to my homeland...}}</ref> in reference to the [[same-sex marriage]] debate and [[Australian survey, 2017 (Marriage)|proposed 2017 survey]] in Australia.<ref name=Aus17>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/tim-minchin-i-still-call-australia-home-ophobic/news-story/75b190ea42a532af92fefaa57aacb8d8|title=Minchin: 'I still call Australia homophobic'|date=11 August 2017|author=Caroline Overington|work=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n*The Australian hip hop group TLK used the song as the inspiration for their 2006 song \"I still call Australia home\" which referenced historical violence against Aboriginals.<ref name=\"Minestrelli2016\">{{cite book|author=Chiara Minestrelli|title=Australian Indigenous Hip Hop: The Politics of Culture, Identity, and Spirituality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vCslDwAAQBAJ|date=26 October 2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-21754-1|page=216}}</ref><ref name=\"PorfilioRoychoudhury2014\">{{cite book|author1=Brad Porfilio|author2=Debangshu Roychoudhury|author3=Lauren M. Gardner|title=See You at the Crossroads: Hip Hop Scholarship at the Intersections: Dialectical Harmony, Ethics, Aesthetics, and Panoply of Voices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-qZBAAAQBAJ|date=23 September 2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-94-6209-674-5|page=136}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3z1scL4kLBs ''I Still Call Australia Home''] TVC (2004)\n* Lyrics: [http://lyriki.com/Peter_Allen:I_Still_Call_Australia_Home Peter Allen - ''I Still Call Australia Home'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m1Oji__RJc0 ''I Still Call Australia Home''] performed in French by Sylvie Boisel\n\n{{Peter Allen}}\n[[Category:Australian patriotic songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag and add authority control template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Still_Call_Australia_Home"}
